3112	\begin{lemma}[Quasi-coherence = a cover with local presentations]
3113	  \label{lem:isQuasicoherent_quasicoherentData_mathlib}
3114	  \lean{SheafOfModules.QuasicoherentData}
3115	  \mathlibok
3116	  \textit{Provided by Mathlib
3117	  (\texttt{Mathlib.Algebra.Category.ModuleCat.Sheaf.Quasicoherent}).}
3118	  A sheaf of modules \(M\) on a scheme is \emph{quasi-coherent}
3119	  (\(\mathrm{IsQuasicoherent}\,M\)) exactly when the type of \emph{quasi-coherence data}
3120	  \(\mathrm{QuasicoherentData}\,M\) is nonempty. A datum
3121	  \(q : \mathrm{QuasicoherentData}\,M\) consists of an index family \(\{X_i\}\) of opens covering the
3122	  whole scheme together with, for each \(i\), a presentation
3123	  \((M.\mathrm{over}\,X_i).\mathrm{Presentation}\) of the restriction of \(M\) to \(X_i\)
3124	  (a cokernel-of-free-modules description on the site over \(X_i\)). Thus quasi-coherence packages a
3125	  cover on which \(M\) is locally presented; on each member of the cover
3126	  \cref{lem:isIso_fromTildeΓ_of_presentation_mathlib} applies.
3127	\end{lemma}
