3229	
3230	\begin{lemma}
3231	
3232	\leanok
3233	[Finite basic-open cover refining a quasi-coherence cover]
3234	  \label{lem:exists_finite_basicOpen_cover_le_quasicoherentData}
3235	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.exists_finite_basicOpen_cover_le_quasicoherentData}
3236	  \uses{lem:isQuasicoherent_quasicoherentData_mathlib, lem:isBasis_basic_opens_mathlib}
3237	  \textit{The topological finite-cover front of the gap1 transport: any quasi-coherence cover refines
3238	  to a finite basic-open cover.}
3239	  Let \(M\) be a sheaf of modules on \(\Spec R\) and let \(q\) be quasi-coherence data for \(M\)
3240	  (\cref{lem:isQuasicoherent_quasicoherentData_mathlib}): a — possibly infinite — open cover
3241	  \(\{q.X_i\}\) of \(\top\) together with a presentation of \(M.\mathrm{over}\,(q.X_i)\) on each
3242	  member. Then there is a \emph{finite} subset \(t \subseteq R\) whose basic opens cover \(\Spec R\)
3243	  (equivalently \(\mathrm{span}\,t = (1)\)) such that each \(D(r)\), \(r \in t\), is contained in some
3244	  member \(q.X_i\) of the presentation cover.
3245	\end{lemma}
3246	\begin{proof}
3247	  \uses{lem:isBasis_basic_opens_mathlib}
3248	  The set \(G = \{\,r \in R : D(r) \le q.X_i \text{ for some } i\,\}\) spans the unit ideal. Indeed
3249	  every prime of \(R\) lies in some member \(q.X_i\) by the covering property \(q.\mathrm{coversTop}\)
3250	  (read off the \(\mathrm{Opens}\) Grothendieck-topology sieve), and the basic opens form a basis of
3251	  the Zariski topology (\cref{lem:isBasis_basic_opens_mathlib}), so a basic open \(D(r) \subseteq
3252	  q.X_i\) is a neighbourhood of that prime; hence \(\bigsqcup_{r \in G} D(r) = \top\), which is to say
3253	  \(\mathrm{span}\,G = (1)\). A unit-ideal membership uses only finitely many of the generators,
3254	  yielding a finite \(t \subseteq G\) with \(\mathrm{span}\,t = (1)\) and each \(D(r) \le q.X_i\) for
3255	  \(r \in t\).
3256	\end{proof}
